Predicting Premier league match results

The Premier League (sometimes referred to as the EPL – English Premier League – outside of the United Kingdom) launched in 1992, and quickly became the #### world’s most popular sports league. Consisting of 20 teams, each club plays their opponents twice in a season, one match home and the other one away,

equaling 38 matches during the course of the entire season that runs from August through May.

it has quickly grown to be one of the largest grossing sport leagues in the world

Defintion of the variables

variable Definition
FTR Full time results
Season season year
Date data and time of match
FTHG Full time home goals
FTAG Full time away goals
HTR half time result
Referee Refree of the match
HTHG Half time home goals
HTAG half time away goals
HS home shots on goal
AS away shots on goal
HST home shots on target
AST away shots on target
HF home fouls
AF away fouls
HC home corners
HY home yellows
AY away yellows
AR away reds
HR home reds

Cleaning the dataset

d1=d
sapply(d, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
##   Season DateTime HomeTeam AwayTeam     FTHG     FTAG      FTR     HTHG 
##        0        0        0        0        0        0        0      924 
##     HTAG      HTR  Referee       HS       AS      HST      AST       HC 
##      924      924     2824     2824     2824     2824     2824     2824 
##       AC       HF       AF       HY       AY       HR       AR 
##     2824     2824     2824     2824     2824     2824     2824
d1$HTR=ifelse(is.na(d1$HTR),d1$FTR,d1$HTR)
d1$HTHG=ifelse(is.na(d1$HTHG),d1$FTHG,d1$HTHG)
d1$HTAG=ifelse(is.na(d1$HTAG),d1$FTAG,d1$HTAG)

we assume that the half time results were the same as the full time results and replace them instead of averages which could skew the algorithm

d1[] <- lapply(d1,function(x) replace(x,is.na(x), sample(x[!is.na(x)],sum(is.na(x)))))
any(is.na(d1))
## [1] FALSE

For the rest of the columns we used lapply and replace the rest of the NA values randomly with other values from the same column, hence we have now a clean dataset.

Prediction of full time results with the help of half time statistics

Subsetting,factoring and dividing into test and train

dmh=subset(d1,select=-c(FTHG,FTAG,Season,DateTime,Referee))
set.seed(420)
dmh$FTR=as.factor(dmh$FTR)
t=dmh$FTR %>% 
  createDataPartition(p=0.8,list = FALSE)
tr=dmh[t,]
te=dmh[-t,]

applying Random forest model

set.seed(420)
mode=randomForest(FTR ~ ., data=tr,proximity=TRUE)

increasing efficiency of mtry

ov=vector(length=20)
for(i in 1:20){
  tempm=randomForest(FTR ~., data=tr,mtry=i,ntree=500)
  ov[i]=tempm$err.rate[nrow(tempm$err.rate),1]
}

Classification algo’s

dzz=d1

mk1=randomForest(FTR~HomeTeam+AwayTeam,data=dzz)
mk2=naiveBayes(FTR~HomeTeam+AwayTeam,data=dzz)

Hence testing the model

k=data.frame(HomeTeam=c("Liverpool"),AwayTeam=c("Chelsea"))
v=predict(hg,newdata=k)
v1=predict(ag,newdata=k)
d0=d1 %>% filter(HomeTeam=="Liverpool" & AwayTeam=="Crystal Palace") 
vv=mean(d0$FTHG)
vv1=mean(d1$FTAG)
ffthg=vv+v/2
fftag=v1+vv1/2
  
kk=data.frame(k,FTHG=c(ffthg),FTAG=c(fftag))
